<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="81.[189,400,1006,1032]" box="[189,400,1006,1032]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,400,1006,1032]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,400,1006,1032]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Brief description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="81.[189,1399,1054,1191]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Monoecious. Receptacle three-celled. Cell I continues in a branched rhizoidal haustorium that penetrates the host. Cell II becomes ± corticated by small cells, some of which giving rise to perithecia or secondary appendages bearing flask-shaped antheridia. Cell III supports a simple primary appendage ending in a solitary spinose flask-shaped antheridium. Perithecium outer wall with four cells for each vertical row.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="81" pageNumber="82" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="81.[189,303,1232,1258]" box="[189,303,1232,1258]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1232,1258]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1232,1258]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="81.[189,1399,1279,1380]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">
The genus consists of two species, of which one in Europe. 
<bibRefCitation author="Benjamin R. K." box="[884,1083,1279,1306]" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" pagination="127 - 137" refId="ref210128" refString="Benjamin R. K. 1985. Morphology and relationships of a new species of Microsomyces (Ascomycetes: Laboulbeniales) from Illinois. Aliso 11 (2): 127 - 137. https: // doi. org / 10.5642 / aliso. 19851102.02" type="journal article" year="1985">Benjamin (1985)</bibRefCitation>
studied the morphology of the genus, especially of the second species, 
<taxonomicName box="[683,961,1316,1342]" class="Laboulbeniomycetes" family="Laboulbeniaceae" genus="Microsomyces" kingdom="Fungi" order="Laboulbeniales" pageId="81" pageNumber="82" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="telephani">
<emphasis box="[683,961,1316,1342]" italics="true" pageId="81" pageNumber="82">Microsomyces telephani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and emended the generic description. This work is a must to understand the complicate morphological structure of thalli in this unusual genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
